          "author": 0,
          "author_avatar_urls": {
            "24": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b39b58f13bbf9c3a24910b7f6178992d950067200a184eb10f45779218b333ab?s=24&r=g",
            "48": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b39b58f13bbf9c3a24910b7f6178992d950067200a184eb10f45779218b333ab?s=48&r=g",
            "96": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/b39b58f13bbf9c3a24910b7f6178992d950067200a184eb10f45779218b333ab?s=96&r=g"
          },
          "author_name": "Chris",
          "author_url": "",
          "content": {
            "rendered": "<p>I shared this post at: <a href=\"https://forum.autonomi.community/t/update-1st-august-2024/40178/23?u=chrisfostertv\" rel=\"nofollow ugc\">https://forum.autonomi.community/t/update-1st-august-2024/40178/23?u=chrisfostertv</a></p>\n<p>Were currently Beta testing the upcoming Autonomi network (p2p) and one of the challenges in running nodes from behind a home router is hole punching/ port forwarding.</p>\n<p>Well I followed your advice, went to static IP to bypass CGNAT&#8230;what a difference. Better internet performance and can run nodes without udp port forwarding.</p>\n<p>All the big node runners are using port forwarding with powerful routers and worrying about NAT table entries&#8230;if that could be bypassed..wow.</p>\n<p>Thanks</p>\n<p>Chris</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s got me excited as it could be of great benefit to an autonomous p2p network and also the ISP&#8217;s as well.</p>\n"
          },
          "date": "2024-08-02T11:53:15",
          "id": 1204,
          "link": "https://www.daryllswer.com/shortcomings-of-cgnat-and-potential-work-arounds/#comment-1204",
          "parent": 0,
          "type": "comment"
        },
        {
          "_links": {
