          "author": 1,
          "author_avatar_urls": {
            "24": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=24&r=g",
            "48": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=48&r=g",
            "96": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=96&r=g"
          },
          "author_name": "Daryll Swer",
          "author_url": "https://www.daryllswer.com/",
          "content": {
            "rendered": "<p>IPTV would be ISP/Unicast specific/Multicast traffic and shouldn&#8217;t be subjected to the load balancing. Create seperate preceding rules for IPTV traffic and ensure it&#8217;s always &#8220;accepted&#8221; before hitting the PCC/Nth rules on the destination IP or port or both. Then you can still use Nth to achieve bandwidth aggregation for everything else.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re an ISP you should be using LACP/Bonding.</p>\n"
          },
          "date": "2022-08-05T04:35:50",
          "id": 8,
          "link": "https://www.daryllswer.com/shortcomings-of-cgnat-and-potential-work-arounds/#comment-8",
